DOCUMENT();
############################################################ # Load Macros ############################################################ loadMacros( "PGstandard.pl", "PGML.pl", "AnswerFormatHelp.pl", "niceTables.pl", "parserAssignment.pl", "contextForm.pl", "PGcourse.pl", ); COMMENT('Authored in PreTeXt');
############################################################ # Header ############################################################ TEXT(beginproblem());
############################################################ # PG Setup Code ############################################################ @x = (0..3); $f = Formula("-1 + 3x"); @y = map{$f->eval(x => $_)} (@x); Context("Numeric")->variables->add(y => 'Real'); parser::Assignment->Allow; parser::Assignment->Function("f"); $eq=Formula("f(x) = $f")->reduce; @t = map{$_*3} (@x);
############################################################ # Body ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML Write an equation in the form [`f(x)=\ldots`] suggested by the pattern in the table.
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML('[`x`]'), rowbottom => '2', midrule => '1',], PGML('[`f(x)`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[1]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[1]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[2]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[2]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[3]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[3]]`]'), ], ], align => 'rl', valign => 'middle',);@]* <<
[_]{$eq}{20}
END_PGML
############################################################ # Solution ############################################################
BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION The relationship between [`x`] and the output in each row is not as clear here. Another popular approach for finding patterns: in each column, consider how the values change from one row to the next. From row to row, the [`x`]-value increases by [`1\text{.}`] Also, the output value increases by [`3`] from row to row.
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML('[`x`]'), rowbottom => '2', midrule => '1',], PGML('[`f(x)`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'), ], [PGML('(add [`1`] from previous) [`[$x[1]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[1]]`] (add [`3`] from previous)'), ], [PGML('(add [`1`] from previous) [`[$x[2]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[2]]`] (add [`3`] from previous)'), ], [PGML('(add [`1`] from previous) [`[$x[3]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[3]]`] (add [`3`] from previous)'), ], ], align => 'r|l', valign => 'middle',);@]* <<
Since row-to-row change is always [`1`] for [`x`] and is always [`3`] for output, the _rate of change_ from one row to another row is always the same: [`3`] units of output for every [`1`] unit of [`x\text{.}`] This suggests that [`f(x)=3x`] _might_ be a good equation for the table pattern. But if we try to make a table with that pattern:
>> [@DataTable( [ [[PGML('[`x`]'), rowbottom => '2', midrule => '1',], PGML('[`3x`]'), PGML('Actual value of [`f(x)`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[0]]`]'), PGML('[`[$t[0]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[0]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[1]]`]'), PGML('[`[$t[1]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[1]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[2]]`]'), PGML('[`[$t[2]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[2]]`]'), ], [PGML('[`[$x[3]]`]'), PGML('[`[$t[3]]`]'), PGML('[`[$y[3]]`]'), ], ], align => '*{3}{c}', valign => 'middle',);@]* <<
We find that the values from [`f(x)=3x`] are too large by [`1\text{.}`] So now we make an adjustment. The equation [`[$eq]`] describes the pattern in the table.
END_PGML_SOLUTION
